<div class='elementListBrownSeparator'></div>
<div class='communityQuestionSubTitle'>
Popular Answered Questions
</div>
<div id='communityQuestionsWithAnswers'>
<div class='communityQuestionAndAnswer'>
<div class='communityQuestion'>
<div class='questionText'>
<div class='spoiler'>
<a class="spoiler" href="/questions/503777-1-why-oh-why-does-donaldson-use-such">This question contains spoilers...</a>
<span class='spoilerAnswerText'>
<a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[1.Why oh why does Donaldson use such pompous pseudo Romantic Gothic 19th Century (a la Walter Scott) language to try to impress us (or rather batter us into awe) . Is it really necessary to say 'need not' and use outdated words like begotten, and my best 'graved' instead of simply buried? <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>
</span>
</div>
</div>
<div class='communityQAFooter questionFooter'>
<ul class='questionFooterActions'>
<li class='footerItem like'>
<span class='likeItContainer' id='like_container_community_question_503777'><a id="like_count_community_question_503777" rel="nofollow" href="/rating/voters/503777?resource_type=CommunityQuestion"><span class="likesCount">2 likes</span></a>&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;<a rel="nofollow" class="jsLike like_it" href="https://www.goodreads.com/user/new?remember=true&amp;return_url=%2Fbook%2Fshow%2F219205.Lord_Foul_s_Bane">like</a></span>

</li>
<li class='footerItem communityQuestionTimestamp'>
<a href="/questions/503777-1-why-oh-why-does-donaldson-use-such">6 years ago</a>
</li>
<li class='footerItem communityQuestionPermalink'>
<a href="/questions/503777-1-why-oh-why-does-donaldson-use-such">See all 7 answers</a>
</li>
</ul>
</div>

</div>
<div class='allCommunityAnswers'>
<div class='communityAnswer'>
<div class='communityAnswerBody'>
<div class='answererUserIcon'>
<a class="leftAlignedImage userPhoto" href="/user/show/49617233-susan"><img alt="" src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/users/1461427081i/49617233._UY100_CR4,0,100,100_.jpg" /></a>
</div>
<div class='communityAnswerTextContainer'>
<span class='communityAnswererName'>
<a href="/user/show/49617233-susan">Susan</a>
</span>
<span class='communityAnswerText'>
<span class="expandableContainer"><span class="truncatedContent">Someone apparently gave Donaldson a thesaurus but not a dictionary. He not only uses antiquated terms but also often uses words that, to borrow from I<a class="jsShow showAction" href="#">…more</a></span><span class="fullContent">Someone apparently gave Donaldson a thesaurus but not a dictionary. He not only uses antiquated terms but also often uses words that, to borrow from Iñigo Montoya, do not mean what he thinks they mean. I see this commonly among students who think they'll appear stupid if they don't use big, fancy words when plain language would get the point across better. It's usually indicative of insecurity. I haven't read anything by Donaldson other than parts of this series, but it might be interesting to read something much more recent to see how (and whether) his prose changed as he became more confident as a writer. I'm not sure, though, that I want to devote the time to that just now.<a class="jsHide hideAction" href="#">(less)</a></span></span>
</span>
</div>
</div>
<div class='communityAnswerFooter'>

<div class='flagAnswer'>
<a class="right flag" rel="nofollow" id="flag_link550520" title="Flag this answer as inappropriate." href="/flagged/new?resource_id=550520&amp;resource_type=CommunityAnswer&amp;return_url=%2Fquestions%2F503777-1-why-oh-why-does-donaldson-use-such%2Fanswers%2F550520-someone-apparently">flag</a>
</div>
<ul class='communityQAFooter answerFooter'>
</ul>

</div>
</div>

</div>

</div>
<div class='communityQuestionAndAnswer'>
<div class='communityQuestion'>
<div class='questionText'>
<div class='spoiler'>
<a class="spoiler" href="/questions/1311992-i-m-about-a-third-of-the-way-through-the">This question contains spoilers...</a>
<span class='spoilerAnswerText'>
<a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[I'm about a third of the way through the book and having a hard time getting through it. Does it improve? I was having a hard time making any emotional connection with Thomas from the start of the book, and it only got worse after the sudden rape scene before he leaves the village; it felt unnecessary and doesn't seem to have done much to really propel the plot forward. <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>
</span>
</div>
</div>
<div class='communityQAFooter questionFooter'>
<ul class='questionFooterActions'>
<li class='footerItem like'>
<span class='likeItContainer' id='like_container_community_question_1311992'><a id="like_count_community_question_1311992" rel="nofollow" href="/rating/voters/1311992?resource_type=CommunityQuestion"><span class="likesCount">3 likes</span></a>&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;<a rel="nofollow" class="jsLike like_it" href="https://www.goodreads.com/user/new?remember=true&amp;return_url=%2Fbook%2Fshow%2F219205.Lord_Foul_s_Bane">like</a></span>

</li>
<li class='footerItem communityQuestionTimestamp'>
<a href="/questions/1311992-i-m-about-a-third-of-the-way-through-the">3 years ago</a>
</li>
<li class='footerItem communityQuestionPermalink'>
<a href="/questions/1311992-i-m-about-a-third-of-the-way-through-the">See all 3 answers</a>
</li>
</ul>
</div>

</div>
<div class='allCommunityAnswers'>
<div class='communityAnswer'>
<div class='communityAnswerBody'>
<div class='answererUserIcon'>
<a class="leftAlignedImage userPhoto" href="/user/show/90877180-todd-peterson"><img alt="" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_100x100-259587f1619f5253426a4fa6fb508831.png" /></a>
</div>
<div class='communityAnswerTextContainer'>
<span class='communityAnswererName'>
<a href="/user/show/90877180-todd-peterson">Todd Peterson</a>
</span>
<span class='communityAnswerText'>
<span class="expandableContainer"><span class="truncatedContent">No, it does not get better. I suppose we are left on our own to ponder the ethics of the rape in a world that he doesn&apos;t really think is real (which, <a class="jsShow showAction" href="#">…more</a></span><span class="fullContent">No, it does not get better. I suppose we are left on our own to ponder the ethics of the rape in a world that he doesn't really think is real (which, other than a couple of mentions, isn't really clear. I suppose that we're supposed to realize that he doesn't think this is real every time he shouts "I'm a leper!" Well, that and the whole naming himself "unbeliever" which I guess we're supposed to keep in the back of our minds. Donaldson over-explains parts that need a good dose of the "show, don't tell" axiom of good writing, while other things are extremely hard to follow/just plain obtuse.<a class="jsHide hideAction" href="#">(less)</a></span></span>
</span>
</div>
</div>
<div class='communityAnswerFooter'>

